etails of Ulmer’s personal life and a thorough analysis of his wide-ranging, eclectic films—features aimed at minority audiences, horror and sci-fi flicks, genre pictures made in the U.S. and abroad. Isenberg shows that Ulmer’s unconventional path was in many ways more typical than that of his more famous colleagues. As he follows the twists and turns of Ulmer’s fortunes, Isenberg also conveys a new understanding of low-budget filmmaking in the studio era and beyond.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMotion picture producers and directorszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh  a20th century directors.  aamerican films.  aaustrian american.  aaustrian directors.  aauteur theory.  ab movies.  adetour.  adirectors.  aeclectic films.  aemigre directors.  afilm criticism.  afilm director.  afilm history.  afilm noir.  afilm.  afilmmaker.  agenre films.  agerman directors.  ahollywood career.  ahollywood.  ahorror films.  ajewish film directors.  alow budget productions.  aminority audience.  amovies.  anoir.  apeople on sunday.  aperforming arts.  apersonal life.  aruthless.  asci fi films.  astudio era.  athe black cat.  aunconventional.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052023577940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095717640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520957176423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520957176/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY